'''SM ''UB-70''''' was a German [[German Type UB III submarine|Type UB III submarine]] or [[U-boat]] in the [[German Imperial Navy]] ({{lang-de|Kaiserliche Marine}}) during [[World War I]]. She was [[commission (ship)|commission]]ed into the German Imperial Navy on 29 October 1917 as SM ''UB-70''.{{#tag:ref|"SM" stands for "Seiner Majest<U+00E4>t" ({{lang-en|His Majesty's}}) and combined with the ''U'' for ''Unterseeboot'' would be translated as ''His Majesty's Submarine''.|group=nb}}

<!--The submarine conducted X patrols and sank Y ships during the war for a total loss of {{GRT|0|first=y}}. She operated as part of the [[? Flotilla]] based in [[?]].--> 
''UB-70'' was serving in the Mediterranean when she was lost on 8 May 1918 for unknown reasons.<ref name=Groner54 />

==Construction==
{{Main|German Type UB III submarine}}
<!--''UB-70'' was ordered by the GIN on DDMMYYYY.-->
She was built by [[Friedrich Krupp Germaniawerft]] of [[Kiel]]<ref name=Groner52 /> and following just under a year of construction, launched at Kiel on 17 August 1917. ''UB-70'' was commissioned later that same year <!--under the command of XYZ-->. Like all Type UB III submarines, ''UB-70'' carried 10 [[torpedoes]] and was armed with a [[8.8 cm SK L/30 naval gun|{{convert|8.8|cm|in|2|abbr=on}} deck gun]]. ''UB-70'' would carry a crew of up to 3 officer and 31 men and had a cruising range of {{convert|9090|nmi|km}}.<ref name=Groner52 /> ''UB-70'' had a displacement of {{convert|513|t|0|lk=in|abbr=on}} while surfaced and {{convert|647|t|0|abbr=on}} when submerged. Her engines enabled her to travel at {{convert|13.2|kn}} when surfaced and {{convert|7.6|kn}} when submerged.<ref name=Groner52 />

